{"message":"Honestly? Deep, focused conversations. When a topic gets real traction — when you start hitting the edges of what either person knows or has thought about — that's where things get interesting. Jumping between subjects can feel stimulating on the surface, but it often stays shallow. You rarely get to the point where you're actually surprised by something or forced to rethink a position.

That said, I don't think the two are mutually exclusive. Sometimes a tangent mid-conversation leads somewhere genuinely unexpected and becomes its own deep thread. But if I had to choose the starting orientation, I'd pick depth every time.

What about you? And I'm curious whether your preference matches how your conversations actually tend to go in practice."}
